definitions.definition: To defeat an enemy and invade in great numbers , seizing the enemy positions conclusively .
To infest , swarm over, flow over.
examples: The vine overran its trellis; the field is overrun with weeds.

definitions.definition: To run past ; to run beyond.
examples: The athlete overran the finish line and kept going.
One line overruns another in length.

subdefinitions.definition: To run past the end of.
examples: The aircraft didn't stop in time and overran the runway.
The performance overran by ten minutes, which caused some people to miss their bus home.

definitions.definition: To carry (some type , a line or column , etc.) backward or forward into an adjacent line or page .
To go beyond ; to extend in part beyond.
examples: In machinery, a sliding piece is said to overrun its bearing when its forward end goes beyond it.

definitions.definition: To abuse or oppress , as if by treading upon.

main_definition: ( transitive ) To defeat an enemy and invade in great numbers , seizing the enemy positions conclusively .
secondary_definitions: ( transitive ) To infest , swarm over, flow over.
( transitive ) To run past ; to run beyond.
( intransitive ) To continue for too long.
( printing ) To carry (some type , a line or column , etc.) backward or forward into an adjacent line or page .
( transitive ) To go beyond ; to extend in part beyond.
( transitive ) To abuse or oppress , as if by treading upon.
